ts to be institutionally recognized as historians. Drawing on interviews and new archival materials to construct a history of Canadian poetry written since 1960, Sharing the Past argues that the project of social history has achieved its fullest expression in lyric poetry, a genre in which personal experiences anchor history. Developing this genre since 1960, Canadian poets have provided an inclusive model for a truly social history that indiscriminately shares the right to speak authoritatively of the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCanadian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSocial history in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aAl Purdy.  aCanadian history.  aCanadian poetry.  aLyric.  aMétis uprisings.  aauthority.  afeminism.  along poems.  alyric historiography.  apoetry.  aregionalism.  asocial history.  awriting history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751232340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487512323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487512323.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles